    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to explain the mathematical and geometric reasons behind why L1 regularization (Lasso) can result in coefficients hitting exactly zero, while L2 regularization (Ridge) only makes them small.\n\nMathematically, L1 regularization adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the coefficients, which can be represented as:\n\nL1 penalty = λ * Σ|β_i|\n\nwhere λ is a regularization parameter and β_i are the coefficients.\n\nOn the other hand, L2 regularization adds a penalty equal to the square of the coefficients, which can be represented as:\n\nL2 penalty = λ * Σ(β_i)^2\n\nNow, let's look at the geometric interpretation. Imagine that you have a set of coefficients that are represented as points in a multi-dimensional space. The L1 penalty creates a diamond-shaped region around the origin, where the penalty is the same for all points on the boundary of the diamond. This means that there are multiple points (sets of coefficients) that have the same penalty value, and one of these points will have at least one coefficient equal to zero.\n\nOn the other hand, the L2 penalty creates a circular region around the origin, where the penalty is the same for all",
